    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>American Agriculture</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Seth Bodner letter warns of potential long-term consequences of proposed radical changes in American agriculture</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Aside from the merits of particular points in ''The Rigged Trade Game'' (editorial, ''Harvesting Poverty'' series, July 20), you propose, in the end, an upheaval in American agriculture.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Aside from the merits of particular points in ''The Rigged Trade Game'' (editorial, ''Harvesting Poverty'' series, July 20), you propose, in the end, an upheaval in American agriculture.</p>
        <p>If that upheaval were in any way like the one currently in progress in the United States' dwindling manufacturing community, you might wish to consider just what the impact would be on the rest of the domestic economy.</p>
        <p>Cotton and corn are no small items on the American economic scene. Drastic dislocation there is not without cost.</p>
        <p>Globalization has come at tremendous costs to the industrial strength of the United States, and with long-term consequences that are as yet unknown.</p>
        <p>A similar program should not be urged for agriculture without examination of the long-term consequences.</p>
        <p>SETH BODNER  Summit, N.J., July 21, 2003</p>
      </block>
